Whenever I go to Din Tai Fung, I always gravitate to their fried rice (in addition to their soup dumplings, of course!), but nowadays eating out is SO EXPENSIVE! Here’s a version you can make in about 30 minutes for a fraction of the cost :) It’s no wonder it’s one of my most popular recipes on the blog!

Din Tai Fung uses Nishiki medium grain rice, but I actually recommend using long grain rice (such as Jasmine rice) here due to the lower moisture content. Since we all don’t have commercial burners at home, I’ve found that the end result is much better on a home stove and less likely to clump up, even when using day old rice!

Since we are in the thick of soup season, I’m re-sharing my Egg Drop Soup that has over 20M views! The silky ribbons of egg are so easy to get with the right technique! If you like longer egg ribbons, pour the egg in a thin, steady stream and then stir to form the ribbons. If you like smaller egg “flowers”, stir the soup and pour the egg at the same time to create those small pedals of flavor! Another key tip - make sure the soup isn’t too hot when pouring the egg, otherwise the soup will become cloudy.

In my family, it wasn’t Thanksgiving unless my grandpa had his Crispy Pork Belly on the table - ultra crispy and juicy and in my opinion so much better than Turkey! My grandpa, or Yeh Yeh, came to the US from China with very little and later after he passed, I later learned that he always made sure we had roast meats like this crispy pork or roast duck on the table because to him, being able to afford these expensive meats meant that he could provide something special for his family, when earlier in his life it was a luxury he wasn’t able to afford. Food was definitely his love language and he instilled in me a love of food. I’m so glad I have the platform to be able to share that love with you!

The traditional method is the best way to get an ultra crispy skin and the juiciest, most flavorful meat in the oven. If you’re an air fryer person, I have a method for that on the blog as well! I hope you’re able to enjoy it this holiday season!

My ground pork stuffing is a delicious twist on a classic version with crispy ground pork seasoned with fragrant five-spice and a touch of Sichuan pepper, guaranteed to be a top tier side dish at your holiday table! I’ve teamed up with the @NationalPorkBoard to create this delicious holiday recipe with the super versatile ground pork that can easily be used in everything from apps, side dishes, or entrees! Visit pork.org for more pork cooking ideas and inspiration and always ensure your ground pork is cooked to 160F – enjoy!

28 oz sourdough bread, cut to 1-inch pieces
1 lb ground pork (80% lean)
1 tbsp oil
1 tsp kosher salt
1/2 tsp Chinese five-spice powder
1/2 tsp Sichuan peppercorn powder
1 tsp sugar
4 tbsp butter
1 large carrot
2 ribs celery
1 yellow onion
2-inch piece ginger
5 cloves garlic
3 scallions, chopped
¼ tsp black pepper
2 tsp kosher salt
1 tsp white pepper
2 ½ cups low sodium chicken broth
2 large eggs

1. Add the bread in a single layer on a baking sheet and bake for 45 minutes at 275F or until dried. Place the bread in a large bowl and set aside.

2. In a bowl, season the pork with salt, five-spice powder, Sichuan peppercorn powder and sugar. Heat a pan over medium high heat and add the neutral oil. Add the pork and cook until 160F and the fat renders and the pork is dark golden brown and crispy. Remove the pork, leaving the fat.

3. To the same pan, add 2 tbsp of butter over medium heat. Add the carrot, celery, onion, garlic, ginger, and scallion whites. Season with salt and black pepper and cook over medium heat for 3-4 minutes or until softened. Deglaze the pan with ½ cup of chicken broth, scraping any fond off the pan, then add back the crispy pork and mix for another minute until combined.

4. Add the mixture directly to the bread and toss to combine. Mix the eggs and remaining chicken broth in a bowl, then slowly add the mixture to the bread until moist. Fold in the scallion greens, then season with salt and white pepper.

5.Place in a greased baking dish and top with remaining knobs of butter and cover with foil. Bake at 425F for 20 minutes then uncover and cook for another 10 minutes or until the stuffing is golden brown.

In my family, ordering a sizzling whole steamed fish at holiday dinner was a MUST (eating it represents abundance and welcomes affluence and wealth for the coming year!). The tender steamed fish with that delicious sauce is so easy to make at home in 20 minutes or less with my go to neutral oil @chosenfoods 100% pure Avocado oil. It’s perfect for bringing the sauce together and blooming those delicious aromatics! You NEED a neutral tasting oil that is well-equipped for high heat cooking (500F smoke point here!) for so many recipes, which is why I always have this oil on hand. @chosenfoods Avocado oil checks all the boxes for me, has good fats from avocados and is always 100% pure! #chosenpartner

Prep 10 minutes
Cook 10 minutes
Serves 4

1 – 1 ½ pound whole fish (sea bass, branzino, snapper), gutted and descaled (ask your fishmonger to do this for you)
3 scallion whites, finely sliced to 2-inch pieces
2” piece ginger, sliced into matchsticks
¼ cup Chosen Foods 100% Avocado Oil
Handful of cilantro, for garnish
 
Sauce
3 tbsp light soy sauce
2 tbsp Chosen Foods 100% Avocado Oil
2 tbsp Shaoxing wine
¼ cup hot water
¼ tsp white pepper
¼ tsp sugar
 
1. Pat the fish dry with a paper towel and make 2-inch-long parallel cuts along both sides of the fish. Place aromatics inside the cavity of the fish.

2. Steam the fish for 8-10 minutes or until the flesh is fully cooked and tender. Pour out any liquid from the fish once steamed.

3. In a small saucepan, add soy sauce, avocado oil, Shaoxing wine, hot water, white pepper, and sugar. Heat until the sugar dissolves and pour this directly over the fish.

4. Add the remaining sliced scallion whites and ginger on top of the fish. Heat the avocado oil to 375F and pour over the hot oil onto the aromatics. Garnish with fresh cilantro and enjoy!

#ad Now that the weather is getting colder, I’m making a deliciously comforting Savory Oatmeal with @quaker Old-fashioned Oats, a versatile blank canvas with a good source of vitamins and minerals per ½ cup of dry oats and can be used for a variety recipes like cookies, cakes, soups, smoothies, or this savory oatmeal! We top ours off with our own favorite toppings for our own unique cozy, comforting meal.

Serves 4

2 cups Quaker Old-Fashioned Oats
1 quart low sodium Chicken Stock 
½ yellow onion, chopped
4 cloves garlic, minced
1 bay leaf
1 tbsp neutral oil (such as vegetable oil)
kosher salt, to taste
black pepper, to taste
2 cups shredded chicken
 
Toppings:
Soft boiled egg
Fried Egg
Chinese Sausage 
Kimchi
Crispy Shallots
Roasted Seaweed
Scallions
Chili Oil

1. In a medium sized pot, heat 1 tbsp of neutral oil over medium high heat. Sauté onions and garlic for 1 minute until fragrant, then stir in the bay leaf for 20 seconds.

2. Add the Quaker Oats to the pot and stir to combine, then add 1 quart of chicken stock and bring to a simmer.

3. Turn the heat to low and simmer for 20-25 minutes or until the oats are cooked, adding the shredded chicken in the last 5 minutes of cooking. If a looser consistency is desired, add ½ cup broth at a time and stir into the oats until the consistency is reached. Season with salt and black pepper, to taste. Remove the bay leaf prior to serving.

4. Transfer the savory oatmeal to a bowl and top with the toppings of your choice!
